            </p>
          </statement>
        </exercise>
      
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Solving_Linear_Equations_in_One_Unknown">
      <title>Solving Linear Equations in One Unknown.</title>

        <activity>
          <title>Work in Groups</title>

          <p>
            <ol>

            <li>
                <p>
                  On one side of a beam balance, place five matchboxes of the same weight.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                On the other side, place two matchboxes.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                To the side with two matchboxes, gradually add grains of sand until the beam balances.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                From both sides, remove two matchboxes and observe whether the beam balances.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Represent the mass of the added sand with a letter and form an equation involving the letter.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Discuss and share your results with other groups.
              </p>
            </li>

          </ol>
          </p>
        </activity>

        <p>
          <term>Learning Points.</term>
        </p>
          
        <p>
        <ol>

          <li>
            <p>
              Subtracting a number from both sides of the equation.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Adding a number to both sides of the equation.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Dividing both sides of the equation by a number.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Multiplying both sides of the equation by a number.
            </p>
          </li>

        </ol>
        </p>

        <example>

        <statement>

          <p>
            Solve the following equation:
          </p>

          <p>
            <me>x + 4 = 7</me>
          </p>
          
        </statement>

        <solution>

          <p>
            Subtract <m>4</m> from both sides.
          </p>
          
          <sidebyside>
            
            <image source="./linear_inequality_sum.png" width="20%">
              <shortdescription>(for accessibility)</shortdescription>
            </image>

            <p>
              <m>\arrowrigth</m>
            </p>

            <image source="./linear_inequality_sum_2.png" width="20%">
              <shortdescription>(for accessibility)</shortdescription>
            </image>

          </sidebyside>

          <sidebyside>

            <p>
              By substracting <me>5</me> from both sides you balance the beam balance which is represents the following equation. <me>x + 4 - 4 = 7 - 4</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              <m>\arrowright</m>
            </p>

            <p>
              Simplifying, we have <me> x = 7 - 4</me>
            </p>

          </sidebyside>

          <p>
              Therefore,  <me>x = 3</me> as shown by the beam balance.
          </p>
          
        </solution>
          
        </example>

        <example>

          <statement>
            <p>
              Solve <me>5x - 3 = 17</me>
            </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>
            <p>
              Adding <m>3</m> to both sides we form this equation;
            </p>

            <p>
              <me>5x - 3 + 3 = 17 + 3</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              Simplifying we get;
            </p>
            
            <p>
              <me>5 x = 20</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              Dividing both sides by <me>5</me> we get;
            </p>

            <p>
              <me>\frac{5x}{5} = \frac{20}{5}</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              Therefore,
            </p>

            <p>
              <me>x = 4</me>
            </p>

          </solution>

        </example>

        <example>

          <statement>
            <p>
              Solve <me>\frac{1}{4}h = 3</me>
            </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>
            <p>
              Multiplying both sides by 4 we have;
            </p>

            <p>
              <me>\frac{1}{4}h \times 4 = 3 \times 4 </me>
            </p>

            <p>
              Simplifying the equation, we get;
            </p>

            <p>
              <me>\frac{4h}{4} = 12</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              Therefore, by cancelling <m>4</m> we have;
            </p>
            
            <p>
              <me>h = 12</me>
            </p>
          </solution>

        </example>

