    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Application_of_Linear_Equations_in_One_Unknown">
      <title>Application of Linear Equations in One Unknown</title>

        <example>

          <statement>

            <p>
              Dorine and Andrew are to share <m>10</m> kg of sugar so that Dorine gets <m>2</m> kg more than what Andrew receives. Find the weight received by each of them.
            </p>

          </statement>

          <solution>

            <p>
              Let Andrew's share be <me>x \text{kg}</me>.
            </p>

            <p>
              Dorine's share <me>= x + 2.</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              Thus, <me>x + (x + 2) = 10.</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              Simplifyinng the equation above we have;
            </p>

            <p>
              <me>2x + 2 = 10.</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              Carrying 2 to the other side and substracting it from <m>10</m> we have;
            </p>

            <p>
              <me>2x = 8.</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              Dividing <m>2</m> in both sides we get;
            </p>

            <p>
              <me>x = 4</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              Which is Andrew's share.
            </p>

            <p>
              To get Dorine's share, we substract Andrew's share from the total share. 
            </p>

            <p>
              <me>10 - 4 = 6</me> which is Dorine's share              
            </p>

            <p>
              Therefore, Andrew's share is <m>4</m> kg and Dorine's share is <m>6</m> kg.
            </p>

          </solution>

        </example>

        <example>
        
          <statement>
            <p>
              Nyambane Real Estate's has a rectangular piece of land which is <m>6</m> m more than its width. 
              If the width is <m>x</m> m and the perimeter is <m>100</m> m, form an equation from this information.
            </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>

            <p>
              The rectangle dimensions of the piece of land are shown below.
            </p>

            <image source="inequality-rectangle.png">
              <shortdescription>Piece of Land</shortdescription>
            </image>

            <p>
              The perimeter is; <me>2((x + 6) + x) = 100 </me>
            </p>

            <p>
              Opening the inner brackets and combining like terms we form the equation; <me>2(2x + 6) = 100</me>
            </p>

          </solution>

        </example>

        <example>

          <statement>

            <p>
              Makanda and Magut sell exercise books at <m>40</m> shillings per book. 
              Peter bought some exercise books from Makanda's shop and from Magut's shop. 
              In Magut's shop, he bought <m>30</m> more books than he bought from Makanda's shop. 
              If he spent a total of <m>4400</m> shillings buying the books, find the number of books bought from each shop.
            </p>

          </statement>

          <solution>

            <p>
              Let the number of books bought from Makanda's shop be <me>x</me>.
            </p>

            <p>
              The number of books bought from Magut's shop is <me>x + 30</me>.
            </p>

            <p>
              Amount spent in Magut's shop <me>= 40 (x + 30).</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              <me>= 40x + 1200.</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              Amount spent in Makanda's shop <me>= 40x.</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              Total amount <me>= 40x + 1200 + 40x</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              <me>= 80x + 1200.</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              Thus <me>80x + 1200 = 4400</me>.
            </p>

            <p>
              <me>80x = 4400 - 1200.</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              <me>80x = 3200.</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              <me>x = 40.</me>
            </p>

            <p>
              Number of books bought from Makanda's shop is <m>40</m> and from Magut's shop is <m>40 + 30</m> = <m>70</m>.
            </p>

          </solution>

        </example>

